## Objective
The objective of this lab is to illustrate **Inter-VLAN Routing** with one physical router interface.
This is done by creating **logical sub-interfaces** (one for each VLAN) and adding IP addresses for each VLAN's default gateway.
---

## Network Setup

### Devices
- **Router:** Cisco 2911
- **Switch:** Cisco 2960-24TT
- **End Devices:** 4 PCs

### VLAN Assignment

- **VLAN 10 (192.168.10.0/24):** PC0, PC1
- **VLAN 20 (192.168.20.0/24):** PC2, PC3

---

## Configuration Steps

### 1. Switch Configuration
Switch> enable
Switch# configure terminal
Switch(config)# vlan 10
Switch(config-vlan)# name Sales
Switch(config-vlan)# exit
Switch(config)# vlan 20
Switch(config-vlan)# name HR
Switch(config-vlan)# exit
Switch(config)# interface fa0/1
Switch(config-if)# switchport mode access
Switch(config-if)# switchport access vlan 10
Switch(config)# interface fa0/2
Switch(config-if)# switchport mode access
Switch(config-if)# switchport access vlan 10
Switch(config)# interface fa0/4
Switch(config-if)# switchport mode access
Switch(config-if)# switchport access vlan 20
Switch(config)# interface fa0/5
Switch(config-if)# switchport mode access
Switch(config-if)# switchport access vlan 20
Switch(config)# interface fa0/0
Switch(config-if)# switchport mode trunk

2. Router Configuration
Router> enable
Router# configure terminal
Router(config)# interface g0/0
Router(config-if)# no shutdown
Router(config)# interface g0/0.10
Router(config-subif)# encapsulation dot1Q 10
Router(config-subif)# ip address 192.168.10.1 255.255.255.0
Router(config)# interface g0/0.20
Router(config-subif)# encapsulation dot1Q 20
Router(config-subif)# ip address 192.168.20.1 255.255.255.0

3. PC Configuration
PC0 (VLAN 10): IP 192.168.10.2 / Gateway 192.168.10.1
PC1 (VLAN 10): IP 192.168.10.3 / Gateway 192.168.10.1
PC2 (VLAN 20): IP 192.168.20.2 / Gateway 192.168.20.1
PC3 (VLAN 20): IP 192.168.20.3 / Gateway 192.168.20.1

Testing

Ping between PCs in the same VLAN → Should work.
Ping between PCs in different VLANs → Should also work (via router sub-interfaces).

Learning Outcomes

How VLANs offer segmentation at Layer 2.
How Router-on-a-Stick facilitates Layer 3 communication among VLANs.
Practical implementation of VLANs, trunks, and router sub-interfaces.

